sentences: José Asunción Flores (27 August 1904 – 16 May 1972) was a Paraguayan composer and creator of the Guarania music genre.
In 1922 he made his first composition, a polka song named "Manuel Gondra".
In 1925, after experimenting with different arrangements of the old Paraguayan song Maerãpa Reikuaase he managed to create a new genre, which he called Guarania.

In 1928 he met the Guairá-native poet Manuel Ortiz Guerrero, and soon after the two started working together to create the most beautiful Guaranias songs to date such as India, Cerro Corá and Panambí Verá.
In 1932 he enrolled in the army to fight for Paraguay in the Chaco War.
In 1944 the song India was declared by the Paraguayan government as a "national song".
Because of his work and contributions to Paraguayan music and culture, Flores was awarded the National Order of Merit in 1949.
Because of that, he was considered "a traitor" by the government and when Alfredo Stroessner became the president of Paraguay in 1954 Flores was forbidden to return to Paraguay.
His wish to return to his home country was even denied in the latter years of his life when he was ill and wanted to see his homeland and people one more time before his death.
Flores died in 1972, in Buenos Aires.
In 1991, after Stroessner was ousted, Flores' remains were brought back to Paraguay, and they rest in a plaza that has his name.
